---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { site } from '../../data/site.js';

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
const href = (url) => {
  if (url.startsWith('http')) return url;
  const cleanBase = base.endsWith('/') ? base.slice(0, -1) : base;
  const cleanUrl = url.startsWith('/') ? url : `/${url}`;
  return `${cleanBase}${cleanUrl}`;
};

const title = "Why New Managers Try to Fix Everything in Week One and Fail";
const description = "New managers rush to prove themselves by changing everything immediately. Here\u2019s why that backfires, and what to do in week one instead.";
const topic = "First Week";
const number = "09";
const longEmbed = null;
const longWatch = null;
const shorts = [];
const related = [
  {
    "title": "How to Run Your First Team Meeting Without Losing Control",
    "slug": "/articles/first-team-meeting-new-manager/",
    "topic": "Meetings"
  },
  {
    "title": "How to Set Boundaries With Former Peers After Promotion",
    "slug": "/articles/boundaries-former-peers/",
    "topic": "Peer Transition"
  }
];

const bookUrl = href('/books/the-first-30-days-as-a-new-manager/');
const articlesUrl = href('/articles/');
const resourcesUrl = href('/resources/');

const schema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'Article',
  headline: title,
  description,
  author: {
    '@type': 'Organization',
    name: 'Plain Act',
  },
  publisher: {
    '@type': 'Organization',
    name: 'Plain Act',
    url: site.siteUrl,
  },
  mainEntityOfPage: new URL(`${base}articles/fix-everything-week-one/`, site.siteUrl).toString(),
};
---

<BaseLayout
  title={title}
  description={description}
  path={`/articles/fix-everything-week-one/`}
  schema={[schema]}
>
  <main class="article-page">
    <nav class="crumbs">
      <a href={articlesUrl}>Articles</a>
      <span>/</span>
      <span>{number}</span>
    </nav>

    <header class="article-hero">
      <p class="kicker">{topic}</p>
      <h1>{title}</h1>
      <p>{description}</p>
      <div class="hero-actions">
        <a href={bookUrl}>Read the book</a>
        <a href={resourcesUrl}>Resources</a>
        {longWatch && <a href={longWatch} target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">Watch video</a>}
      </div>
    </header>

    {longEmbed && (
      <section class="media-block">
        <div class="video-frame long">
          <iframe
            src={longEmbed}
            title={title}
            loading="lazy"
            allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share"
            allowfullscreen
          ></iframe>
        </div>
      </section>
    )}

    <article class="article-body">
      <h1>Why New Managers Try to Fix Everything in Week One and Fail</h1>
<p>Week one feels like you have to prove you deserved the promotion.</p>
<p>So you fix things. Meetings, processes, tools, priorities, roles. All at once. Fast.</p>
<p>By week three, half those changes are reversed, the team is exhausted, and you’ve burned credibility you hadn’t earned yet.</p>
<p>Fixing everything in week one is not leadership. It is anxiety in action.</p>
<h2>What usually happens</h2>
<p>Day two, you see a messy process. You change it. Day three, you change the meeting cadence. Day four, you reassign tasks. Day five, you announce a “new way of working”.</p>
<p>None of these changes are bad individually. The problem is speed and volume. The team went from a stable manager to a tornado in five days.</p>
<p>People start whispering: “Just wait, they’ll change it back next week.” And often, you do, because you changed things before you understood why they were that way.</p>
<p>You also miss the real problems, because you’re busy fixing visible ones. The loud process is rarely the broken one. The quiet bottleneck is.</p>
<p>Meanwhile, the team is spending energy adapting to your changes instead of doing the work. Output drops. You think they’re resisting. They’re just tired.</p>
<h2>Why this becomes a problem</h2>
<p>You lose trust. Change without context feels random. Random change feels unsafe. Unsafe teams slow down.</p>
<p>You fix the wrong things. You don’t have enough data in week one to know what actually needs fixing. You’re fixing symptoms you can see, not causes you haven’t found yet.</p>
<p>You create change fatigue immediately. If week one is five changes, what is month two going to be? People brace instead of engage.</p>
<p>You can’t follow through. Five changes at once means zero changes followed through well. Half-implemented changes are worse than no changes.</p>
<h2>The mistake managers make</h2>
<p>The mistake is confusing motion with progress.</p>
<p>New managers think: if I change things fast, they’ll see I’m serious.</p>
<p>What the team sees: this person doesn’t understand how we work yet, and they’re changing it anyway.</p>
<p>Authority in week one does not come from change. It comes from observation.</p>
<h2>What to do instead</h2>
<p>Week one: Observe. Listen. Note. Change nothing structural.</p>
<p>Use Listen / Map / Pick One.</p>
<p><strong>1. Listen.</strong> Do 1:1s with every direct report in the first 5 days. 20 minutes each. Three questions only: What’s working? What’s stuck? What would you change if you were me? Write it down. Don’t promise fixes. Just listen.</p>
<p><strong>2. Map.</strong> After the 1:1s, map what you heard. What came up three times or more? That’s your real priority list. Not the messy spreadsheet you noticed on day two.</p>
<p><strong>3. Pick One.</strong> Choose ONE change for week two or three. The smallest change with the biggest relief. Announce it clearly, implement it fully, follow through. One well-executed change builds more authority than five rushed ones.</p>
<p>Everything else goes on a “later” list. Tell the team: “I heard X, Y, Z. We’re starting with X this week. Y and Z are next.” That transparency alone builds trust. They feel heard, and they see you can prioritize.</p>
<p>Resist the urge to “leave your mark” in week one. Your mark in week one is: steady, listening, not breaking anything. That is rarer than you think, and more respected.</p>
<h2>Example</h2>
<p><strong>Fix-everything version:</strong> Week one: new meeting structure, new task tracker, new roles, new deadlines, new reporting format. Team spends the week learning your systems instead of shipping. Two good people start updating their resumes.</p>
<p><strong>Observe-first version:</strong> Week one: 1:1s with everyone. Listen only. End of week: “Thanks everyone. Top three themes I heard: unclear priorities, slow approvals, meeting overload. Next week we’re fixing priorities first – one shared board, updated Mondays. The other two are coming after.” One change, clearly explained, tied to what the team told you. That lands. That builds buy-in.</p>
<p>Then actually fix priorities in week two. Fully. Then move to approvals in week three. Sequential, calm, complete.</p>
<h2>How to apply this this week</h2>
<ol>
<li><strong>Freeze structural changes for 7 days.</strong> No new tools, no process rewrites, no reorgs. Observe only. Write down what you want to change, don’t act yet.</li>
<li><strong>Run 1:1s with three questions.</strong> What’s working? What’s stuck? What would you change? 20 minutes each. Take notes.</li>
<li><strong>Build a “heard list”.</strong> After 1:1s, tally repeats. Top 3 themes = your real roadmap. Share that list with the team.</li>
<li><strong>Pick ONE change for next week.</strong> Smallest effort, biggest relief. Execute it completely before touching the next one.</li>
<li><strong>Tell the team what you’re NOT changing yet.</strong> “I’m not touching the reporting format this month.” That sentence alone reduces anxiety. People fear the unknown change more than the known problem.</li>
</ol>
<h2>Final note</h2>
<p>You were promoted to improve things. You will. Not in week one.</p>
<p>Week one is for listening and mapping. Week two is for one clean change. Week three is for follow-through.</p>
<p>Slow is fast in month one. Observe first, fix second. The team will trust your changes a lot more when they see you understood before you acted.</p>
<p>This article is based on the Plain Act approach to early management pressure.</p>
<p>---</p>
    </article>

    {shorts.length > 0 && (
      <section class="shorts-section">
        <p class="kicker">Shorts</p>
        <h2>Short clips from this lesson</h2>
        <div class="shorts-grid">
          {shorts.map((short, index) => (
            <div class="short-frame">
              <iframe
                src={short.embed}
                title={`${title} short ${index + 1}`}
                loading="lazy"
                allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share"
                allowfullscreen
              ></iframe>
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>
      </section>
    )}

    <section class="cta-box">
      <p class="kicker">Plain Act</p>
      <h2>The First 30 Days as a New Manager</h2>
      <p>A practical manual for first-time managers carrying authority, feedback, delegation, and decision pressure.</p>
      <div class="hero-actions">
        <a href={bookUrl}>Open the book page</a>
        <a href={articlesUrl}>Back to articles</a>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="related">
      <p class="kicker">Related</p>
      <div class="related-grid">
        {related.map((item) => (
          <a class="related-card" href={href(item.slug)}>
            <span>{item.topic}</span>
            <strong>{item.title}</strong>
          </a>
        ))}
      </div>
    </section>
  </main>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .article-page {
    max-width: 920px;
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: 2.6rem 1.2rem 4rem;
  }

  .crumbs {
    display: flex;
    gap: 0.45rem;
    align-items: center;
    margin-bottom: 1.4rem;
    color: var(--muted);
    font-size: 0.9rem;
  }

  .crumbs a {
    color: var(--accent);
    text-decoration: none;
  }

  .article-hero {
    max-width: 780px;
  }

  .kicker {
    margin: 0 0 0.6rem;
    color: var(--accent);
    font-size: 0.78rem;
    letter-spacing: 0.14em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    font-weight: 700;
  }

  .article-hero h1 {
    margin: 0;
    font-size: clamp(2.1rem, 5vw, 4.4rem);
    line-height: 0.96;
    letter-spacing: -0.06em;
  }

  .article-hero p {
    margin-top: 1rem;
    color: var(--muted);
    font-size: 1.06rem;
    line-height: 1.65;
  }

  .hero-actions {
    display: flex;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    gap: 0.7rem;
    margin-top: 1.2rem;
  }

  .hero-actions a {
    color: var(--text);
    text-decoration: none;
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: 999px;
    padding: 0.55rem 0.82rem;
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    background: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.035);
  }

  .media-block {
    margin: 2rem 0;
  }

  .video-frame {
    position: relative;
    overflow: hidden;
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: 1rem;
    background: #05070a;
    box-shadow: 0 24px 70px rgba(0,0,0,.2);
  }

  .video-frame.long {
    aspect-ratio: 16 / 9;
  }

  .video-frame iframe,
  .short-frame iframe {
    position: absolute;
    inset: 0;
    width: 100%;
    height: 100%;
    border: 0;
  }

  .article-body {
    margin-top: 2rem;
    padding: 1.2rem 0;
    color: var(--text);
  }

  .article-body :global(h1) {
    display: none;
  }

  .article-body :global(h2) {
    margin-top: 2.1rem;
    margin-bottom: 0.7rem;
    font-size: clamp(1.35rem, 2.5vw, 2rem);
    letter-spacing: -0.035em;
  }

  .article-body :global(h3) {
    margin-top: 1.6rem;
  }

  .article-body :global(p),
  .article-body :global(li) {
    color: var(--muted);
    line-height: 1.78;
    font-size: 1rem;
  }

  .article-body :global(strong) {
    color: var(--text);
  }

  .article-body :global(blockquote) {
    margin: 1.2rem 0;
    padding: 1rem 1.1rem;
    border-left: 3px solid var(--accent);
    background: rgba(255,255,255,.035);
    color: var(--text);
    border-radius: .75rem;
  }

  .shorts-section,
  .cta-box,
  .related {
    margin-top: 2.2rem;
  }

  .shorts-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(3, minmax(0, 1fr));
    gap: .85rem;
  }

  .short-frame {
    position: relative;
    aspect-ratio: 9 / 16;
    overflow: hidden;
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: .9rem;
    background: #05070a;
  }

  .cta-box {
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: 1.2rem;
    background: rgba(255,255,255,.035);
    padding: 1.2rem;
  }

  .cta-box h2 {
    margin: 0;
    font-size: clamp(1.45rem, 3vw, 2.4rem);
    letter-spacing: -0.04em;
  }

  .cta-box p {
    color: var(--muted);
    line-height: 1.6;
  }

  .related-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(2, minmax(0, 1fr));
    gap: .85rem;
  }

  .related-card {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: .45rem;
    color: var(--text);
    text-decoration: none;
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: 1rem;
    padding: 1rem;
    background: rgba(255,255,255,.035);
  }

  .related-card span {
    color: var(--accent);
    font-size: .75rem;
    letter-spacing: .12em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
  }

  @media (max-width: 760px) {
    .shorts-grid,
    .related-grid {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    }
  }
</style>
